Vegan Foods and Regular Foods

Shuhan Song

1/26/2020

Introduction

The food nutrient data provided by FoodData Central contains information about nutrients and other components in foods and food products. To explore the different nutrients and energy supplies in vegan and regular diets, I used PCA and biplots to analyze energy level (kcal), protein (g), fat (g), and carbohydrate (g) in vegan and regular foods and food products. I included all food groups for regular diet and Spices and Herbs, Breakfast Cereals, Fruits and Fruit Juices, Vegetables and Vegetable Products, Nut and Seed Products, Legumes and Legume Products, and Cereal Grains and Pasta for vegan diet.

Made with logoMakr on Jan.26, 2020.

Result

Vegan foods and food products

nutrient <- read_csv(here("data", "usda_nutrients.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names() 

unique(nutrient$food_group)
##  [1] "Dairy and Egg Products"              "Spices and Herbs"                   
##  [3] "Baby Foods"                          "Fats and Oils"                      
##  [5] "Poultry Products"                    "Soups, Sauces, and Gravies"         
##  [7] "Sausages and Luncheon Meats"         "Breakfast Cereals"                  
##  [9] "Snacks"                              "Fruits and Fruit Juices"            
## [11] "Pork Products"                       "Vegetables and Vegetable Products"  
## [13] "Nut and Seed Products"               "Beef Products"                      
## [15] "Beverages"                           "Finfish and Shellfish Products"     
## [17] "Legumes and Legume Products"         "Lamb, Veal, and Game Products"      
## [19] "Baked Products"                      "Sweets"                             
## [21] "Cereal Grains and Pasta"             "Fast Foods"                         
## [23] "Meals, Entrees, and Side Dishes"     "American Indian/Alaska Native Foods"
## [25] "Restaurant Foods"
# vegan food
nutrient_vegan <- nutrient %>% 
  filter(food_group %in% c("Spices and Herbs", "Breakfast Cereals", "Fruits and Fruit Juices", "Vegetables and Vegetable Products", "Nut and Seed Products", "Legumes and Legume Products", "Cereal Grains and Pasta" )) %>% 
  select(energy_kcal:carb_g) %>% 
  rename(Energy = energy_kcal,
         Protein = protein_g,
         Fat = fat_g,
         Carbohydrate = carb_g)
# check number of missing
skimr::skim(nutrient_vegan)
# regular food
nutrient_reg <- nutrient %>% 
  select(energy_kcal:carb_g) %>% 
  rename(Energy= energy_kcal,
         Protein = protein_g,
         Fat = fat_g,
         Carbohydrate = carb_g)
# check number of missing
skimr::skim(nutrient_reg)
# pca

# vegan
pca_vegan <- prcomp(nutrient_vegan, scale = TRUE)

sum_vegan <- summary(pca_vegan)

biplot_vegan <- autoplot(pca_vegan,
                         alpha = 0.1,
                         #colour = NA, # point color
                         loadings.label.size = 3,
                         loadings.label.colour = "black",
                         loadings.label = TRUE,
                         loadings.label.repel = TRUE) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-0.065, 0.065)) 
  
biplot_vegan

Figure 1: Biplot for main nutrients in vegan foods and food products. The first two PCs had a cumulative 85.69% of variance. Energy level is correlated with protein, fat and carbohydrates. Data source: FoodData Central

Regular foods and food products

# regular
pca_reg <- prcomp(nutrient_reg, scale = TRUE)

sum_reg <- summary(pca_reg)

biplot_reg <- autoplot(pca_reg,
                       alpha = 0.1,
                      #colour = NA, # point color
                      loadings.label.size = 3,
                      loadings.label.colour = "black",
                      loadings.label = TRUE,
                      loadings.label.repel = TRUE) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-0.04, 0.04)) 
  
biplot_reg

Summary

  • Energy level of vegan foods and food products is correlated with protein, fat and carbohydrates with protein having the highest correlation.

  • Energy level of regular foods and food products is correlated with fat and carbohydrates while protein has almost no correlation with energy. Instead, fat had the highest correlation with energy.

  • Both vegan and regular foods and food products were clustered.
